      question: "How does net metering actually work with TEP, and do I really get full credit for the extra power my panels produce?",
      answer: "Yes—Arizona's net metering law requires TEP (Tucson Electric Power) to credit you at full retail rates for excess solar production sent to the grid, making solar economics excellent in Tucson. Here's exactly how it works: Your solar panels produce electricity during sunny hours (typically 6 AM to 6 PM). When production exceeds your home's instantaneous consumption (common during midday when AC might be the only major load), excess power flows backward through your meter to TEP's grid. Your bi-directional meter tracks both consumption from grid and export to grid, running forward when you draw power and backward when you export power. TEP credits your account at full retail rates ($0.12-0.14/kWh standard rate, $0.16-0.22/kWh for time-of-use peak periods) for every kWh exported. These credits roll over month-to-month indefinitely, offsetting evening and nighttime grid consumption when solar doesn't produce. At year-end, any remaining excess credits are typically forfeited (they don't pay you cash), so systems are sized to produce 90-100% of annual consumption, not dramatically more. On TEP's optional time-of-use rate plans, afternoon solar production (2-7 PM) earns the highest credit rates ($0.18-0.22/kWh) coinciding with peak AC demand—perfect timing. You'll still receive a monthly TEP bill showing grid charges (typically $12-$25/month in connection fees even with solar) and net consumption/credits. Properly sized systems reduce annual TEP bills from $1,800-$3,600 down to just $150-$300 in remaining fees and minimal winter grid usage. Net metering makes solar financially viable—without it, solar payback would be 12-15+ years instead of 6-9 years. Call (520) 333-2665 for detailed net metering analysis with your actual TEP bills."
